Preheat your oven to 200°C. Pour a good glug of oil onto a #baking tray{} and pop in your
oven. Bring a large #saucepan{} of water for the potatoes to the boil on high heat with a
pinch of @salt{pinch}. Peel the @potatoes{900%g}, chop them into 4cm chunks. Halve, peel
and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. Pick the @rosemary{1%sprig} leaves from their stalks
and finely chop (discard the stalks). Peel and trim the @parsnips{2} and @carrots{3}.
Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges
have softened when you poke them with a knife.

Heat a splash of oil in a #frying pan{} over medium heat and add half the
@butter{30%g}. Stir in the onion and cook, stirring frequently until soft and
caramelised, ~{15-20%minutes}. Lower the heat if the onions are browning too quickly.
Meanwhile, chop the parsnips and carrots into roughly 1cm wide, 5cm long batons.
Arrange on another baking tray and drizzle with oil. Season with @salt{}, @pepper{} and
half of the @dried thyme{1/2%tsp}. Toss to coat.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle
on the rosemary and half the @flour{24%g}. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven,
carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil.
Sprinkle over a pinch of salt. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven for
~{45-50%minutes}, turn halfway through.

Season the @British beef roasting joint{450%g} with salt, pepper and the remaining thyme.
Transfer to the baking tray with the potatoes.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Roast in the oven for 35/45/55 mins (depending on size) for medium rare. Add an extra
~{5%minutes} if you like your beef more cooked. Rest wrapped loosely in #foil{} for at
least ~{10%minutes} before slicing.

> IMPORTANT: The beef is safe to eat when the outside is browned and cooked.

Roast the parsnips and carrots in the middle of the oven until soft and golden at the
edges, ~{30-40%minutes}.

When the onions are soft and golden, sprinkle on the remaining flour and stir to coat.
Cook the flour for ~{1%minute}, then gradually stir in the @water{400%ml}, and
@beef stock powder{1}. Bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that may form. Lower
the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Pop a frying pan on medium heat with the remaining butter and @cavolo nero{1} and
stir-fry for ~{2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper then add a splash of water.
Cover with a #lid{} or foil and cook until tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When you are ready to serve, reheat the gravy and stir the @redcurrant jelly{1}. Drizzle
the @honey{1} on the roots, toss to coat and reheat if necessary.

Slice the beef and arrange on your plates. Pop the roasties, carrots, parsnips and
cavolo nero alongside. Finish with lashings of onion gravy and enjoy!